AB  - Segregation refers to the degree to which social groups are spatially, and, by implication, socially separated from one another. Related to this concept is the extent to which people in an area, such as a neighborhood, have similar social characteristics. Such characteristics have tended to be empirically measured in terms of ethnicity or social class. This is largely because cities, predominantly in the US, have shown tendencies to separate social groups by income and race following riots in the late 1960s, social housing policies and suburbanization by higher-income groups. A key question, related to issues of segregation, is whether the spatial separation of social groups is a problem in its own right (wherein, living in a poor or socially homogeneous area may reinforce poor life chances) or whether these patterns are also symptomatic of deeper social problems and prejudices. Much of the research literature on segregation has assumed, in any case, that it forms a significant social and urban problem, but it has generally been difficult to identify commonly agreed-upon measures of its prevalence and impact. These various issues relate to a number of conceptual problems, as well as the availability of adequate data. In contemporary Western urban contexts, segregation has continued to be a prominent feature of city life which reflects, in part, not only the rising income inequalities but also a fear of crime and social difference. In countries such as the UK segregation has deepened around income, rather than ethnic, lines, while in the US it would seem that both income and ethnicity are important in explaining patterns of spatial clustering by particular social groups. An emerging research issue has been to acknowledge that patterns of residential segregation, essentially measures representations of social life contained in neighborhoods, may usefully be supplemented by an understanding of patterns of mobility and separation within and between areas. Thus, we now acknowledge dynamic forms of social separation wherein like-with-like social association may occur in social networks across space as well as within the neighborhood context. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.
